Sex, Sexing Modernity: Prostitution in Early-Twentieth-Century Shanghai -- t8. Approximations of Chinese Bandits: Perverse Rebels, Romantic Heroes, or Frustrated Bachelors? -- tPART V . THE GENDER OF REBELS (CULTURAL REVOLUTION) -- tIntroduction -- t9. Maoist Mappings of Gender: Reassessing the Red Guards -- t10. “Little Brothers” in the Cultural Revolution: The Worker Rebels of Shanghai -- tPART VI . BLOOD, QI, AND THE GENDERED BODY (QING DYNASTY AND REFORM ERA) -- tIntroduction -- t11. Blood, Body, and Gender: Medical Images of the Female Condition in China, 1600 –1850 -- t12. Embodying Qi and Masculinities in Post-Mao China -- tPART VII . SHIFTING CONTEXTS OF GENDER AND SEXUALITY (REFORM ERA) -- tIntroduction -- t13. Past, Perfect or Imperfect: Changing Images of the Ideal Wife -- t14. Proper Men and Proper Women: Parental Affection in the Chinese Family -- tPART VIII . GENDER, SEXUALITY, AND ETHNICITY (REFORM ERA) -- tIntroduction -- t15. Gender and Internal Orientalism in China -- t16. Tradition and the Gender of Civility -- tAfterword: Putting Gender at the Center -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe past two centuries have witnessed tremendous upheavals in every aspect of Chinese culture and society. At the level of everyday life, some of the most remarkable transformations have occurred in the realm of gender. Chinese Femininities/Chinese Masculinities is a mix of illuminating historical and ethnographic studies of gender from the 1700s to the present. The essays in this highly creative collection are organized in pairs that alternate in focus between femininity and masculinity, between subjects traditionally associated with feminism (such as family life) and those rarely considered from a gendered point of view (like banditry). The chapters provide a wealth of interesting detail on such varied topics as court cases involving widows and homosexuals; ideal spouses of early-twentieth-century radicals; changing images of prostitutes; the masculinity of qigong masters; sexuality in the era of reform; and the eroticization of minorities. While most of the essays were specifically written for this volume, a few are reprinted as a testament to their enduring value. Exploring the central role of gender as an organizing principle of Chinese social life, Chinese Femininities/ Chinese Masculinities is an innovative reader that will spark new debate in a wide range of disciplines.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFemininityzChina. 0aMasculinityzChina. 0aSex rolezChina. 4aGender Studies. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aBrownell, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrownell, Susan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChen, Nancy N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDillon, Nara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Harriet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFurth, Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlosser, Susan L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHershatter, Gail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHonig, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJankowiak, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaqueur, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaqueur, Thomas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLarson, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLitzing